# SECTION AAA - M3.48 router classifier fixes + post-fix paired test (2026-05-03, $0.065)
#
# Operator authorized $1 budget (research-first per atom 0018). This
# turn used $0.065 of the remaining $0.93 (research-first kept costs low).
#
# ROUTER CLASSIFIER FIXES (atom 0017 byproduct from M3.47):
#   - phd-factual check moved BEFORE math-chain (Heisenberg's "ℏ/2"
#     symbol falsely triggered math-chain; phd-factual takes priority)
#   - phd-factual keyword expansion: heisenberg, uncertainty principle,
#     relativity, wavefunction, schrödinger, entropy, enzym, protein,
#     molecul (was: only quantum/chem/biolog/physic/gpqa/research-paper)
#   - hard-reasoning keyword expansion: chameleon, knights and knaves,
#     invariant argument, mod-N-invariant, parity argument, monovariant
#     (was: only AIME/olymp markers + specialized geometry)
#   - math-chain keyword expansion: sum of digits, compute.*\d,
#     calculate.*\d, evaluate expression, 2^/10^/n^ (was: missing
#     "compute"-style framings)
#   - bounded-code keyword expansion: reverse.*string, one-line.*function
#
# 21/21 router pytest tests still green after classifier fixes.
#
# M3.48 PAIRED TEST POST-FIX (5 tasks, same as M3.47):
#
# | Task | Shape (post-fix) | Target | Cost ratio | Notes |
# |------|------------------|--------|------------|-------|
# | T1 bounded-code | bounded-code | claude-haiku-4.5 | **1.502×** | auto MORE EXPENSIVE on simple task |
# | T2 math-chain | math-chain | deepseek-v4-flash | 0.013× | ~75× cheaper |
# | T3 phd-factual | phd-factual | gemini-2.5-flash | 0.301× | ~3× cheaper |
# | T4 multistep-general | multistep-general | gpt-5-mini | 0.067× | ~15× cheaper |
# | T5 hard-reasoning | hard-reasoning | [voter cheap×2+smart_C] | n/a (untracked) | 7× SLOWER (40s vs 5.4s) |
# | AGGREGATE | — | — | **0.085× (11.7× cheaper)** | latency 1.64× slower from voter |
#
# HONEST atom-0013 DISCLOSURES (load-bearing nuance):
#
# 1. T1 bounded-code routing to haiku-4.5 was MORE expensive ($0.001232
#    vs gpt-5.5 $0.00082) on a tiny one-liner task. haiku-4.5 produces
#    markdown code-block formatting (~30 token overhead) while gpt-5.5
#    at low reasoning effort produces raw code. For ULTRA-SIMPLE
#    bounded-code tasks, gpt-5.5 direct may be cheaper than haiku
#    routing. Future v2.x router refinement candidate (per atom 0017).
#
# 2. T5 hard-reasoning voter pattern fired (chameleon-keyword catch
#    working as designed post-fix) but took 40 seconds vs gpt-5.5
#    direct at 5.4 seconds — 7× SLOWER on this task. Voter caught no
#    error (both gpt-5-mini and gpt-5.5 produced correct "No" with
#    mod-3-invariant reasoning). Voter overhead was REPRODUCTIVE WASTE
#    on this task. Per atom 0020 + atom 0021: voter should be reserved
#    for tasks where cross-witness genuinely catches errors. v2.x
#    router refinement candidate: tighter "fire voter only when
#    expected-error-rate justifies overhead" logic.
#
# 3. Aggregate cost still 11.7× cheaper (close to M3.47 12.2×) — the
#    bounded cost-dominance claim HOLDS post-fix.
#
# 4. Aggregate latency 1.64× SLOWER (was 1.01× parity in M3.47 because
#    voter didn't fire; M3.48 fired voter on T5 adding 35 seconds of
#    sequential cheap×2 + smart_C overhead). HONEST: cheapcode is NOT
#    uniformly faster than gpt-5.5; voter pattern adds latency.
# ============================================================

